 Britain’s relations with the Far East from the start of his working life at fourteen, to his death at fifty-seven. Orphaned at the age of five, he went to China on his own as a child and worked his way to the top. God-fearing and fearless, he believed his mission was to bring trade and ‘civilisation’ to East Asia. In his day, he was seen as both a hero and a monster and is still bitterly resented in China for his part in the country’s humiliations at Western hands, but largely esteemed in Japan for helping it to industrialise. Morton’s new biography, the first in over thirty years, and benefiting in part from access to the Parkes’ family and archives, offers a more intimate and informed profile of the personal and professional life of a Victorian titan and one of Britain’s most undiplomatic diplomats in the history of the British Civil Service.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDiplomatsvBiographyzGreat Britain. 0aDiplomatszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aDiplomats-Great Britain-Biography. 0aGreat Britain-Foreign relations-Japan. 0aParkes, Harry,-Sir,-1828-1885. 4aAsian Studies. 4aBiography: historical, political and military. 4aDiplomacy. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aEast Asia, Far East. 4aInternational Relations. 4aPolitics and Government. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aCivil Service.  aDiplomacy.  aEast Asia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781912961177?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781912961177423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781912961177/original  a978-3-11-068955-6  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_E